      <acqinfo id="aspace_543b6b5fcef0b1ef4c1708ce697a3a36">
         <head>Immediate Source of Acquisition</head>
         <p>W. S. Lewis purchased most of the material from Myers &amp; Co., Ltd., in January 1948. Bequest of Wilmarth Sheldon Lewis (Yale 1918), 1979.</p>
         <p>Additional material has been and will be acquired from various sources. For more information see the finding aid.</p>
      </acqinfo>
      <arrangement id="aspace_17b933b99a6f9ca36db6511c95b116c1">
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <p>Organized into three series: I. Letters to Montagu, 1740-1785. II. Letters from Montagu, 1741-1779. III. Other Papers, 1909.</p>
      </arrangement>
      <bioghist id="aspace_f9e490cfdcd22e5e95bf4be297e5b22e">
         <head>Elizabeth Robinson Montagu (1718-1800)</head>
         <p>Elizabeth Robinson Montagu was born in Yorkshire, the daughter of Matthew Robinson (1694-1778) and Elizabeth Drake Robinson. Both she and her sister Sarah Robinson Scott (1720-1795) were educated in languages and literature, and both became writers. In 1742 she married Edward Montagu (1692-1775) of Northumberland, and the couple had one child, John, who died in 1744. The Montagus maintained residences in Northumberland, Berkshire, London, and Bath; in London and Bath Elizabeth Montagu became a respected host noted for her literary salons that attracted writers and artists, both male and female, for intellectual conversation. She founded, led, and hosted the Blue Stockings Society, an informal discussion circle composed of educated and privileged women and men.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <custodhist id="aspace_2039421d7d197dcdcb3ff842e6d43f8e">
         <head>Custodial History</head>
         <p>Library records indicate that the Montagu letters Wilmarth S. Lewis acquired from Myers &amp; Co., Ltd., in January 1948 "were removed from a large fol. vol. of autograph letters labeled 'Autograph Letters Relating to Bath, 1602-1830'" before he bought them from Myers &amp; Co., Ltd. Those letters present are identifiable by the glassine hinge strips (some with album page paper still attached) along one vertical border. They are also mentioned in Emily J. Climenson's three letters in Series III, which were marked as having come from the same album though their hinge strips and attached album page paper is different, suggesting that Climenson had mounted her collection in an album that she sold to the recipient of her letters, and her own letters were added on separate leaves by the album's new owner. Climenson's letters may even have been addressed to Myers &amp; Co. founder Albert Myers, who had opened as Albert I. Myers, Antiquarian Booksellers at 59 High Holborn, London, in 1901. Climenson had published her two-volume edition of Montagu's correspondence, <title>
               <part>Elizabeth Montagu, the Queen of the Blue-stockings</part>
            </title>, in London in 1906 and was likely familiar with the Myers shop.</p>
         <p>The album was apparently dismantled once it entered the Myers firm. Material that Lewis purchased separately is identified at the folder level, if the vendor is known.</p>
         <p>Prior to February 2024 the material in LWL MSS 49 had been interfiled in the Lewis Walpole Library Manuscript Miscellany (formerly LWL MSS MISC, now LWL MSS 36). The material in Box 1, Folders 1-23 was purchased by Wilmarth S. Lewis; all material in boxes and folders following those was purchased by the Lewis Walpole Library, Yale University.</p>
      </custodhist>
      <prefercite id="aspace_b97b396bcbf80507dc2b66dde2689e1d">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
         <p>Elizabeth Montagu Collection. The Lewis Walpole Library, Yale University.</p>
      </prefercite>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_329c16cddc5c5588056086b9f1abac4e">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The Elizabeth Montagu Collection contains letters to and from her friends and relatives. Family highlights include twenty letters Montagu wrote to her husband Edward, ten letters to and from her sister Sarah Robinson Scott, and one from her brother brother, Matthew Robinson-Morris, Baron Rokeby, who wrote his opinion of their cousin Elizabeth Lumley marrying the author Laurence Sterne, whom he described as "a Parson, who once delighted in debauchery." Also present are communications to and from Montagu's bluestocking friends including Anne Donnellan, Margaret Cavendish-Harley, Duchess of Portland, Ann Dillingham Ord, Benjamin Stillingfleet, and Elizabeth Vesey, as well as family friends Rev. William Freind and Dr. John Gilbert. The outlying correspondence is three letters from 1909 written by Montagu's editor Emily J. Climenson; they came with the collection and provide provenance documentation.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      <userestrict id="aspace_7e3fe4b051e8f9b8950f8537e3cfaaae">
